    <title>Hello, World!</title>
    <link href="https://yourdomain.com#2021-01-11-hello-world"/>
    <updated>2021-01-11T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <id>https://yourdomain.com/#2021-01-11-hello-world</id>
    <content type="html">&lt;h1&gt;Hello, World!&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;"Hello, World!" program&lt;/strong&gt; generally is a &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_program" title="Computer program"&gt;computer program&lt;/a&gt; that outputs or displays the message "Hello, World!". Such a program is very simple in most &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language"&gt;programming languages&lt;/a&gt;, and is often used to illustrate the basic &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syntax" title="Syntax"&gt;syntax&lt;/a&gt; of a programming language. It is often the first program written by people learning to code.&lt;sup&gt;&lt;a href="#" class="footnote-ref"&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;  It can also be used as a &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanity_test" title="Sanity test"&gt;sanity test&lt;/a&gt; to make sure that a computer language is correctly installed, and that the operator understands how to use it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="footnotes"&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;James A Langbridge (3 December 2013). &lt;a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=y51NAgAAQBAJ&amp;amp;pg=PA74"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Professional Embedded ARM Development&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" title="ISBN (identifier)"&gt;ISBN&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781118887820" title="Special:BookSources/9781118887820"&gt;9781118887820&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;#160;&lt;a href="#" class="footnote-backref"&gt;&amp;#8617;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
